<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
General appearance as in Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 136–142" captionStartId="F25" captionText="Figures 136 - 142. Peplometus biscutellatus, male 136 habitus, dorsal view 137 habitus, lateral view 138 venter of abdomen 139 cheliceral dentition 140 first leg, dorsoprolateral view 141 first leg, dorsal view 142 palpal organ, ventral view (photos - specimen from Ghana, drawings - specimen from Sierra Leone)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures136-142" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427076" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">136</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 136–142" captionStartId="F25" captionText="Figures 136 - 142. Peplometus biscutellatus, male 136 habitus, dorsal view 137 habitus, lateral view 138 venter of abdomen 139 cheliceral dentition 140 first leg, dorsoprolateral view 141 first leg, dorsal view 142 palpal organ, ventral view (photos - specimen from Ghana, drawings - specimen from Sierra Leone)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures136-142" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427076" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">137</figureCitation>
. Body flattened, completely covered with strongly sclerotised and pitted integument. Dorsum of body dark brown, clothed in dense short white hairs (lost in some of the studied specimens). Eye field on more than half of carapace length, black rings around eyes, the first row of eyes encircled with white hairs. Long white bristles between anterior eyes. Clypeus extremely low, brown with a few white hairs. Chelicerae with three diminutive teeth on promargin and five retromarginal teeth fused basally (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 136–142" captionStartId="F25" captionText="Figures 136 - 142. Peplometus biscutellatus, male 136 habitus, dorsal view 137 habitus, lateral view 138 venter of abdomen 139 cheliceral dentition 140 first leg, dorsoprolateral view 141 first leg, dorsal view 142 palpal organ, ventral view (photos - specimen from Ghana, drawings - specimen from Sierra Leone)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures136-142" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427076" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">139</figureCitation>
). Mouthparts brown. Sternum oval, brown. Abdomen elongated, widest anteriorly and tapering rearward, anterior edge almost straight. Dorsum of abdomen totally covered by very strongly sclerotised and pitted scutum, laterally slightly turned back to venter. Venter with typical scuta; anterior scutum narrow, extending backwards laterally, posterior ventral scutum largest, cordiform. In front of epigastric furrow a thin sclerotised plate with thick posterior margin forms narrow wedge-shaped bar. Numerous bumps on sides ventrally; armour-plate pattern is shown in Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 136–142" captionStartId="F25" captionText="Figures 136 - 142. Peplometus biscutellatus, male 136 habitus, dorsal view 137 habitus, lateral view 138 venter of abdomen 139 cheliceral dentition 140 first leg, dorsoprolateral view 141 first leg, dorsal view 142 palpal organ, ventral view (photos - specimen from Ghana, drawings - specimen from Sierra Leone)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures136-142" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427076" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">138</figureCitation>
. Spinnerets brown, obscured by dorsal scutum. Legs I the biggest, femora enlarged, brownish with darker prolateral side, three short spines on dorsum. Tibia thickened, clearly flattened prolaterally, blackish with pale dorsal streak, ventrally black brash of dense long feather-shaped setae (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 129–135" captionStartId="F24" captionText="Figures 129 - 135. First leg of male 129 Pachyballus castaneus 130 Peplometus biscutellatus 131, 132 P. chlorophthalmus 133 P. congoensis 134 P. oyo 135 P. nimba 132 retrolateral view, others prolateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures129-135" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427075" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">130</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 136–142" captionStartId="F25" captionText="Figures 136 - 142. Peplometus biscutellatus, male 136 habitus, dorsal view 137 habitus, lateral view 138 venter of abdomen 139 cheliceral dentition 140 first leg, dorsoprolateral view 141 first leg, dorsal view 142 palpal organ, ventral view (photos - specimen from Ghana, drawings - specimen from Sierra Leone)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures136-142" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427076" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">140</figureCitation>
), metatarsi and tarsi short, yellowish, two pairs of ventral spines on metatarsi. Other legs pale yellowish with dark marks at bases of segments, only femora IV brown (or yellow with brown streak on prolateral side). Palps light, their structure as in Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 136–142" captionStartId="F25" captionText="Figures 136 - 142. Peplometus biscutellatus, male 136 habitus, dorsal view 137 habitus, lateral view 138 venter of abdomen 139 cheliceral dentition 140 first leg, dorsoprolateral view 141 first leg, dorsal view 142 palpal organ, ventral view (photos - specimen from Ghana, drawings - specimen from Sierra Leone)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures136-142" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427076" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">142</figureCitation>
. Palpal tibia short with single thin straight apophysis, bulb oval, embolus thin, long, spirally coiled, forming three loops on bulb tip.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Female.</emphasis>
Measurements: Cephalothorax: length 1.0-1.4, width 1.2-1.4, height 0.5-0.6. Eye field: length 0.6-0.8, anterior width 1.0-1.2, posterior width 1.2-1.3. Abdomen: length 2.1-2.3, width 1.7-1.9.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
General appearance as in Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 143–145" captionStartId="F26" captionText="Figures 143 - 145. Peplometus biscutellatus, female 143, 144 habitus, dorsal view 145 habitus, ventral view (143 specimen from Cameroon 144, 145 specimen from Ghana)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures143-145" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427077" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">143-145</figureCitation>
. Similar to male, but abdomen wider, heart-shaped. Scarce white hairs on body. Carapace dark brown, black near eyes. Legs I as in males, not so thick, tibia slightly thickened, retrolateral flattening hardly visible. Palps dark, blackish. Epigyne large, rectangular, weakly sclerotised, with small semicircle shallow depression divided by median septum (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 146–149" captionStartId="F27" captionText="Figures 146 - 149. Peplometus biscutellatus, female, epigyne (upper row specimens from Sierra Leone, lower row specimens from Ghana)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures146-149" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427078" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">146-149</figureCitation>
). In some females horizontal crevices laterally, formed by microsculpture of integument, not part of epigyne (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 146–149" captionStartId="F27" captionText="Figures 146 - 149. Peplometus biscutellatus, female, epigyne (upper row specimens from Sierra Leone, lower row specimens from Ghana)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures146-149" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427078" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">146</figureCitation>
). Copulatory ducts very long, spirally coiled behind openings, form several loops distally, spermathecae bean-shaped (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 150–153" captionStartId="F28" captionText="Figures 150 - 153. Peplometus biscutellatus, female, internal structure of epigyne 150, 151 ventral view 152, 153 dorsal view (150, 151 specimen from Ghana 152 specimen from Cameroon 153 specimen from Sierra Leone)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures150-153" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427079" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">150-153</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
